@Article{	  Schwarz1994,
  abstract	= {A mark-recapture experiment was conducted applying a
		  two-sample stratified technique to estimate the number of
		  Atlantic salmon smolts, Salmo salar, migrating out of the
		  Conne River, Newfoundland. We developed a model where
		  parameters are introduced to describe the mean time for the
		  salmon to migrate between the release site and recapture
		  site and to describe the probability of capture on a
		  particular date. The latter are then used to expand the
		  number of untagged smolts captured to estimate the daily
		  run sizes. We discuss the advantages of this new approach
		  over other models. For example, this formulation allows
		  great flexibility in the experimental design, is robust to
		  violations of assumptions, and allows the influence of
